{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645382"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:17:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:17:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18112"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18112"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.18,0.79,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73559"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10826"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18112"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59028"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7166"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25199"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73559"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of nerve roots forms the brachial plexus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C4-C8","C4-T1","C5-T1","C5-T2","C6-T2"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brachial plexus is formed by the anterior rami of the \u003Cstrong\u003EC5-T1\u003C/strong\u003E spinal nerve roots. These roots combine to form trunks, divisions, cords, and finally the peripheral nerves that innervate the upper limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC4-C8\u003C/strong\u003E - This range includes C4, which is not part of the brachial plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC4-T1\u003C/strong\u003E - This range includes C4, which is not part of the brachial plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC5-T2\u003C/strong\u003E - This range includes T2, which is not part of the brachial plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC6-T2\u003C/strong\u003E - This range excludes C5 and includes T2, which is not part of the brachial plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The brachial plexus is formed from the anterior rami of the C5 to T1 spinal nerve roots.","The brachial plexus is responsible for the motor and sensory innervation of the upper limb.","The brachial plexus is a network of nerves that extends from the neck to the axilla."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"